{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1441dc84-4d41-413b-bf64-22974b2c741a","content":"## Using MCP Inspector with a C# stdio Server\n\nRun the inspector with `npx`:\n\n```bash\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector dotnet run --project /path/to/YourServer.csproj\n```\n\nThis launches a web UI (typically at `http://localhost:5173`) that proxies stdio communication to your server.\n\n**From the Inspector UI you can:**\n- Browse available tools, resources, and prompts\n- Send `tools/call` requests with custom arguments\n- View raw JSON-RPC messages for debugging\n\n**Tips:**\n- If your server needs env vars, pass them with `-e KEY=VALUE` before the command.\n- Add `--server-url` if the default port conflicts.\n- Ensure your server writes MCP JSON-RPC to **stdout** and logs to **stderr** — any stray stdout output will break the protocol.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"07f286d0-d349-472e-9e80-5bd921ad688d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to use the MCP Inspector to test and debug a C# MCP server that uses stdio transport. This is a general knowledge question about MCP (Model Context Protocol) tooling. Let me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":269,"requestId":"CBC0:331FF:1887FC5:1BBCA03:69FE8906"},"id":"4284d0c8-df73-48d6-8969-5662447c2e97","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:08:31.376Z","parentId":"6871398b-718d-4d3f-af58-b0c42e217b50"}
